The holiday season is a time to come together, especially around the dinner table. 

Unfortunately, millions are at risk of losing their food stamps also known as SNAP. We will continue to work to protect vulnerable children and families. #HandsOffSNAP pic.twitter.com/xoG40evZ8X

There are thousands of Black migrants trying to get into our country who have been invisible in the immigration debate.

Last Friday, we went across the border to bring more attention to this issue.

We must continue to face this crisis head-on. pic.twitter.com/O0uejBBarB

Yesterday, I held an official hearing at our border to understand where the United States is with regard to humane treatment of migrants. 

We must do better. pic.twitter.com/iKyS3PqgMU

I’ve been to our immigration facilities. 

I’ve seen the children. 

I’ve met the families. 

On Friday, I’ll be chairing an official congressional hearing at the border to highlight the humanitarian crisis there. 

It’s time for action.

"Was there a quid pro quo? As I testified previously, with regard to the requested White House call and White House meeting, the answer is yes.”

– A firsthand witness with direct contact with President Trump, Giuliani, Mulvaney, Bolton, Pompeo and the rest.

They all knew. pic.twitter.com/W6PhMq1FF3

In summary, President Trump demanded a favor from President Zelensky in his own political interest, not national interest, in return for the favor of a White House visit. Is that accurate?

Lt. Colonel Vindman: Yes. pic.twitter.com/YM9DaPrIdF

First they had an issue because we were in a confidential setting, then they wanted transcripts, then it was too public.

After this week they'll run out of procedural arguments and have to say "well sure it happened it just wasn't that serious."

There was a crime. They know it. pic.twitter.com/MVqDDgzrw1

The Trump administration has fired the person in charge of addressing homelessness throughout the country. That seems to be a counterproductive step in addressing this growing epidemic. https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/11/16/trump-administration-ousts-top-homelessness-official-white-house-prepares-broad-crackdown/ …

10 people were shot last night in Fresno at a football watch party. 

We passed bipartisan, commonsense gun violence prevention legislation more than 260 days ago. 

What will it take for the Senate to act? https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/18/us/fresno-mass-shooting-football-party/index.html …

Ambassador Yovanovitch is a patriot who has dedicated more than 30 years of her life to serving this country and fighting corruption.

After a smear campaign, she was fired, setting the stage for Trump to press Ukraine to investigate a political rival.

It’s all connected. pic.twitter.com/HW8bHTGsEV

Sometimes we put pressure on other countries and sometimes we address issues of international corruption. 

Trump wasn't doing either of these things. He was using the power of his office to try to influence another country for his own personal political gain. 

Period. pic.twitter.com/SKw48OXPiD

Reports are breaking now of a shooting at Saugus High School in Santa Clarita. 

When children go to school, they should not have to fear for their lives.

Calling the whistleblower to testify in public would destroy the whole concept of protecting people who take the courageous step forward to point out wrongdoing in the government. 

Whistleblowers must remain protected. pic.twitter.com/w9yl3WgMzQ

The President abused the power of his office to try to influence the 2020 election to his advantage. 

The President is not above the law. 

He will be held accountable. pic.twitter.com/zH0BUkvEtS

I can't believe it took until 2019, but today the House Judiciary Committee passed a resolution to facilitate ratification of the Equal Rights Amendment, which will guarantee equal legal rights for all American citizens regardless of sex.

Proud to be a part of this vote.
Day one of public hearings in the historic impeachment inquiry. pic.twitter.com/nvVlCT11Pk

Hoy, la Corte Suprema tiene en sus manos el futuro de más de medio millón de personas, muchas de las cuales solo conocen a este país como su hogar. 

Hoy, nuestras voces se unen como una.

Estoy con nuestros Dreamers.

#NuestroHogar

Today, the Supreme Court holds the futures of more than half a million people – many of whom have only known this country as their home – in their hands. 

Today, our voices come together as one. 

I stand with our Dreamers. 

#HomeIsHere

This year we’ve passed more than 20 bills for veterans addressing issues ranging from suicide prevention to housing insecurity. 

To our vets, including Fmr. Army Specialist William Manheim -- we will continue to honor your service. #VeteransDay pic.twitter.com/WietTv3NpN

There needs to be a standard for the way women are treated in prisons. 

Anyone who has given birth can tell you that the last thing on your mind while you’re in labor is getting off of the bed and running. 

The shackling of pregnant women in prisons must be abolished totally.

It's been over 200 days since the House passed the Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act of 2019. 

It’s time the Senate took action to reauthorize #VAWA. 

Our community depends on it. pic.twitter.com/IpW7U2GC6U

11 years ago today, Barack Obama was elected President. 

Now in LA, you can drive down President Barack Obama Boulevard. pic.twitter.com/iph5hTYG87

This week, students at Vermont Avenue Elementary School had the opportunity to ask @astro_luca any question in the world.

He answered from space. 

These are the young people in our community. Who said our future isn't bright? pic.twitter.com/ztrY8aSbhA

In July, I called a hearing to look specifically at how women in prison are treated. 

Comprehensive reforms to address the ways women are entrapped in our system, how they’re treated in jail, and what happens upon release is on the way. https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/house-judiciary-subcommittee-meets-discuss-growing-population-women/story?id=64352816 …

They say that if the good guys have guns, mass shootings would stop. 

Time and time again, we see that's a myth. With weapons of war on our streets, it doesn't matter. 

We will only solve this gun epidemic if we pass bold policies and allocate sufficient resources. pic.twitter.com/0TCHLYOJXZ

Last week, Trump gave Turkey the green light to slaughter our Kurdish allies, the same ones who helped us kill Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi.

This week I voted to sanction Turkey for their attacks on the Kurds.

We cannot have our foreign policy run by tweet. https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/29/us/politics/house-turkey-sanctions.html …

Trump has a history of empowering private citizens to operate in the shadows to do his bidding. 

Case in point: Corey Lewandowski pic.twitter.com/0aSDSukIvG
